re than\n00 murders and killinKs' set i down by\nwsj offices as \"unsolved,\" th'e new year\nas hal set for,it,('a penny-dreadful record\nwill lake two Rln men from Coyotj\nanjon a lifetime's endeavor to beat.\nA r'de from the Grand Central in a tax\nicab, now is conceded by leading papers\nhe \"Dead wood stagei'oa'h and the biff\nxuAh mid restaurants loom uj as cheery\ns the' Santa Fe saloon in the Wild West\n'ays ot the -fix-gun toter and the Bay Boy\nr' t'to citv to have nothing on a trip in\niaiid't': i f F.loody Hollow. Twenty po\n'ico rillemen patrol the streets at night\nn automobile-. The curfew rings out at\nnidniglit when Central Bark is closed to\nvehicular and pedestrian traffic, and all\n;,etsons abroad must give account of them\nelves v.hen asked.\nJn the ji.-ist nonth judges on the crimi\nnal courts bench have urged formation of\nritizens' committees on a par with the\nvigilantes of the frontier before it was\naccused of moving back east to metropoli\ntan centers. The mayor has warned all\npersons carrying or possessing valuables\nI t procure 'permits to arm themselves\nagainst highwaymen and the police have\ntried to get back to something like first\nprinciples in life and property protection,\nCrimes have been. chronicled as though\nthev were robbery and murder cyclones,\nand the subway newspaper reader has felt\nall the thrill of riding the Overland Lim\nited in the days when Jesse James and\nhis gang held no prairie railroad immune\nfrom their ravages.\nEstimates have placed about $4,000,000\nas-the total value 'of loot obtained by\nburglars, thieves and yeggmen in New\nVl, ,l.,-;.wr ieCf- Tfai-Kiri,' lnlltirw it.\ntnebvj in lending tireat Ulot.Wflv hotels\nand automobilef banditry, Jjaye, yielded\nmuch of the val.uajblesr'stqlen.-t Vs many\ntured for a month's ctof vionce of\nunto nin six mum trcnH)fs in a c av\nj Of the inoije than Kr -\"unsolved\" mur-\nders listed by? some pajiers. a number now\nare nationairy, n dot. internationally.\nUnnwii. Beumnimr with n killinar last\nNew Year's day. 102H's record starteel\nlist were the murderx of Joseph B. Klwell,\nMiss Uenie Constance lloie. and FreVl\neiick C. Kckert. Klvwll, known from coast\nto coast as a whist expert and horseman,\nwas shot to death in his handsomely fur\nnished West 70th street home: Miss\nHoxie, a 17-year-old girl, was found muti\nlated in her father's house: Kckert. a for\nmer government agent and alleged whis\nkey runnei, was found shot dead in an\nautomobile in Staten Island.\nJn the robberies organized bands of\ngunnfen have seemed to predominate.\nThefts of valuable goods .'from railroad\nfreight cars, bulking big in packing cases,\nhave been considerable. Stolen automo\nbiles have been reported constantly. But\nholdups of the old-time type, by day as\nwell as night, on the street, in the home,\nin hotels, where masked and unmasked\nmen have taken what they, wanted at the\npoint of pistols, have called forth the hue\nand cry against alleged \"inadequate police\nprotection.\"\nAutomobile bandits 1: ve made off with\na number of factory payrolls and banks\nhave seen gunmen waik in and .demand\nmoney lrom the safe under penalty of in\nstant death.\nALL,' POWDERED FACES\n.KE TO BE SLArrED.\nPRESIDENT TO\nACT ASJEOIATOR\nGoing Ahead With Plans\nfor Turco-Armenian\nSettlement\nMORGENTHAU MAY\nPAY OWN EXPENSES\nThe President's decision to become\nmediator was approved pretty generally\nby t he American, press irrespective of\nparty, on the ground that anything that\nmight be done to help the cause of the\nArmenian pople who have suffered so\nmuch would be a step toward solving\nthe Near Eastern problems. where\nAmerican missionaries have labored so\nlong to stimulate the processes of civilization.\nNEW HELIUM GAS\nPLANT IN TEXAS\nManley Brothers Go. Inc.\nBATTERY SERVICE STATION\nHigh Street Brattleboro, Vermont\nFact that the Present Administration\nCloses March 4 Vnlikely to Interfere\nWith Wilson's Plan to Help League of\nNations Settle Dispute.\nBy DAVID LAWRENCE.\n(Sp-ial Despatch to The Reformer.)\nCopyright 1!21.\nWASHINGTON. Jan. S. President\nWilson plans to go ahead with his work\nof mediation as between Armenia and\nthe Turkish nationalists. So far as the\ninformation in official quarters is con\ncerned (here is 'lot basis for1 the\" report\nthat the British and French governments\nare trying to discourage Mr. Wilson\nproceeding with the task since he is to\nleave the presidency within the next six\nweeks. The suggestion was made by\nPrime Minister Lloyd George that Mr.\nWilson designate the American high\ncommissioner at Constantinople to act\nfor him and this has given rise to the\nbelief that the British government\nwanted to get the task of mediation\ninto official channels .since the Amer\nican high commissioner is an officer of\nthe department of state aud as such\nwould continue in office beyond March\n4 and his acts would be those of the\nUnited States government.\nBut it is now officially explained that\nthe prime minister's suggestion was made\non Dec. 2 in a note to the council of\nthe league of nations before word reached\nthe other side that Mr. Wilson had de\ncided to apiHiint former Ambassador\nHenry Morgenthau. The note reached\nhere only a few days ago, having been\nforwarded through the council of the\n-league and thus delayed. British offi\ncials here say the suggestion was made\nas a supplementary rather than an al\nternative proiosal and that there was\nno desire on tho part of the prime minis\nter to change the spirit of the decision\nof the league council to accept Mr. Wil\nson as mediator. It is pointed out at\nthe state department that the league\ncouncil formally .acknowledged Mr. Wil\nson's message iu which he said he could\nnot act for the government of the\nUnited Urates but only as a private in\ndividual and could not, of course, fur\nnish troops or any other power to back\nI up the decisions he might make. Mr.\nH llsou, moreover, asked for the moral\nsupiKtrt of all the governments on the\ncouncil of the league so that his deci\nsions would bo backed up. The league\nin acknowledging Mr. Wilson's message,\nrenlie! tbnt if vnnl! be flnil In linve\nhim serve.\nI From this exchange of messages ofli\nj cials here are proceeding on the theory\nthat all is smooth and that the govern\nments of Europe fully understand the\nunique position in which Mr. Wilson\nis placed by reason of his retirement\nfrom office on March 4. by which tune\nof course, hardly a beginning could be\nmade in the task of mediation. It is\nunderstood that for the time being, at\nleast, Mr. Morgenthau. who will repre\nsent the president in the negotiations be\ntween the Armenians and Turkish na\ntionalists, will pay his own exicnses\nthough no doubt. the league of nations\nwill subsequently reimburse him.\nIt js not improbable that Mr. uson\nmay ask the next administration to con\ntinue the work of mediation if the mat\nter requires governmental machinery and\ncannot be handled as a personal media\ntion though this is not expected. There\nhave been many instances in which dis\ntinguished statesmen and jurists have\nbeen requested to, .act ..'as 'mediators in\ninternational disputes and, their govern\nments have been in no Way involved. It\nh the 'reliance of, both sides in the fair\nness of the individual rather than the\nphysical help of his government which\nis most desired in mediating disputes.\nGovernment Establishment Costing\nOOO.OOO Nearly Done To Ojierate\non Large Scale Soon.\nFOUT WORTH, Texas, Jan. x.-Ki.Uh-illtf\ntouches are being put on the federal\n1 governments S.l,O0O,0flO helium uas plant\nsix miles -north ot tort Worth, and op\nerations on a large scao- are expected to\nReein soon.\nj This announcement i.s made bv Lieu\ntenant Grimn. who is in charge, as the\nrepresentative of the navy department.\nThe last cf the machinerv was snipped to\nFort Worth befoie the firet of the year.\nEstablished in 1017 at a cost of ssoo.ooo,\nthe plant has been an experiment sta\ntion thus far. But the worth of the pi\nand its o-oiioniy for -use by the ;iav and\narmy balloons have been proved to the\nsatisfaction of militaiy experts.\nJn addition at ...the. plant near Fort\nWorth, the goverwf'ient also has con\nstructed a private pipe- lmc from Pet fo\nlia whirli brhlgs natural jms trom-f he\nLone Star Coniany's wells riht into the\nplant. After the argon qualities, from\nwhich helium is obtained, have been ex\ntracted, the gas is returned to the mains\nami burned by Fort Worth and other\nconsumers in northern Texas.\nThe argon or helium plant was erected\nir. great secrecy, a guard of soMieis be\ninc constantly maintained around it un\ntil after the armistice. During war days,\nadmission was denied to the public a ,7ft\nonly picket! workmen' were employed.\nThe experiments at the station had\nbeen so successful liefore the armistice\nthat it was pi edict ed the use of the ar\ngon gas would speedily terminate the\nconflict. However, no opportunity was\never given of testing it out in battle.\nThe gas is non-inflammable and non\ncombustible. Its value was discovered be\nfore the war but the process of extrac\nting it was then too costly to make the\ngas practical. Government agents have\nsince jtorfected an economical method.\nThe gas is shipped from Fort Worth\nto Galveston and New Orleans in cylin\nders and loaded there aboard navy de\npartment vessels for transportation to\nballoon fields.\nZION, III., Jan. 8. Hereafter\nwomen in the Zion tabernacle will ap\npear with unpowdcred noses or Over\nseer Yolvia will \"lecture them and\nslap their faces,\" according to an\nedict lie delivered yesterday.\n\"The tabernacle is not a boudoir,\"\nthe overseer proclaimed. The use\nof the worldly .powder puff is a -violation\nof the sanctity of God's house. I j\nhavec seen, women \"right in this faber-\nnacle dabbiiigr away with powder\npuff barefacedly. ItXX?- sacrilege\nand a disgrace. t f\n\"You'll coine here unpowdered and\nyou'll cover your bodies as my grand-\nmother covered hers or I'll lecture\nyou i and slap your faces instead cf\npowdering them.'\nST. ALBANS WINS\nFONDA TAX CASE\nSupreme Court 3Iakes Decision in Estate\nInvolving Over Half a Million\nto City in Taxes.\nST. 'ALBANS. Jan. X. Probably the\nmost important case of the kind before\nthe Vermont mpreme court in a great\nmany years, has resulted in a victory\nfor the city of St. Albans. The case was\nthat of St. Albans against the Fonda\nheirs and it will give, St. Albans SlO,\nOOO a year in taxes.\nBoecher Fonda died in Fcbrurary,\nlitis, leaving more .tlmn. .half a million\nto four heirs in St. Albans. The estate\nwas settled within the .year. On com\ning into pos.scs.sion of the proiH-rty the\nheirs made a conveyance in trust to the\nOld Colony Trust Co.\nWhen the listers railed on tho heirs\nfor tax inventories they claimed the\nproperty was not taxable as it had been\nconveyed to the Old Colony Trust Co.\nThe trust agreement provided that the\nheirs might revoke the trust at any time\nand take the property back in their own\nhands. Also, they might control the in\nvestment of the property. The income\nof all the property was paid to heirs and\nprovision was made for a disposition of\nthe trust.\nThe city claimed that the projrty\nwas taxable ami assessed the heirs for\nthe amount of the property.\nThe question before the supreme court\nwas to whether this property was tax\nable to these heirs, or beneficiaries, or\nwhether the fact that it had been turned\nover to the Old Colony Tnist Co. put\n(he property .beyond the jurisdiction of\ni lie city or St. Albans or the state of\nVermont to tax.\nThe supreme court decided that the\nproperty was taxable to the Fonda heirs\nin St. Albans. Justice Slack read the\nopinion.\nThe heirs were represented by George\nM. Hogan and the old lirm of Diinnett.\nShields Conant. The city of St. Al\nbans was represented by Itoswell Aus\ntin, city attorney, ami 'Judge Charles\nII. Darling of Burlington.\nHUNTRES\nS-ADA\nMS CO\nAnother Extraordinary\nBargain\nIN OUR AFTER NEW YEAR'S\nMARK DOWN\nLadies' Fleece Lined Vests\nand Pants\nRegular and extra sizes. Have been selling\nall the season for $1.75-31.95,\nBargain Price 95c\nWe are offering hundreds of equally good\nvalues in eveiy department from the Second\nFloor to the Basement. Bigger Mark Downs for\nEqual Value than You Would Expect to Find in\nAny Store.\nCOME AND SEE FOR YOURSELVES\nDon't Overlook Our Special Offering of\nSurplus Stock\nColumbia $1.00 Records\nClean-Up Price 69c\nNot a big lot of them, but Records by some of\nthe best artists. For a few days only.\nAMKNDED OK REPEALED.\nEASLES\nmay be followed by serious\ncold troubles; use nightly\nPI\nVapoRuq\nOver 1 7 Million Jan Used Yearly\nSouth Dakota Blue Liw Must Be Made\nEnforceable, Officials Say.\nPH'.BKH. S. D.. Jan. N. South Da\nkota's blue laws must either be repealed\nor amended so they may be enforced,\nin the opinion f Attorney Jeneral\nPayne, who declares the wording of\npresent statutes leads to evasion of tho\nlaw's intent.\n\"tiainful occupations\" are prohibited\nin South Dakota on Sundays, but no\nsection, of the statutes defines just what\nare \"gainful occupations.\"\nTherefore baseball, motion pictures,\ndancing, theatres, lioxing and various\nother things that, it is declared, the law\nwas designed to prohibit on Sundays,\nare made legal by lack of specification,\naccording to the attorney general.\nProiMuicnts of a \"blue Sunday\" in this\nstate are eager to have the legislature\nat its coming session amend the blue\nlaws and enlarge their scoih so that they\nmay seoifically cover all forms of\namusement ami commerce not \"abso\nlutely essential.\"\ni On the other hand sentiment appears\nto be developing in favor of the rejH-al\nof all blue laws. Backers of this pro\nposition urge among other things that\nthe prohibition of Sunday baseball would\nmean the death of the South Dakota\nleague.\nCADET FOI ND DEAD.\nCause of Death of West Point Student\nNot Known.\nWEST POINT, X. Y.. Jan. S. Dennis\nTotten of Milford,- Vt li, a cadet at the\nmilitaiy academy, was found dead on the\nreservation yesterday. A board of officers\nis investigating the cause of death, Which\nhas not yet been determined.\nTotten was a third-class man, having\nbeen a cadet at the academy for n year\nand a half. Officials of the academy said\nlast night that Totten had not been la\ngood health recentlyand that probably\nwhile ill he wandered off about 15.40 p. in,\nThursday ami was not seen again until\nhis body was- found yesterday morning.\nThe board of officers investigating his\ndeath will make a report of their findings\ntoday.\nA Human Bouquet.\nRocky Mountain Telegram Miss\nThomas was a lovely picture in rose\npink organdy with hat to match. She\ncarried an armful of pink gladiators.\ni Boston Transcript.\nMANY WOMEN\nSTILL IN INDUSTRY\nOnly Part of Those Employed During\nWar Period Have Lost Place,\nSince .Men's Return.\nl-Mlt'ACO, dan. 8. Only part of the\nwomen enMied in industry duijii the\nwas pel iod h;ive lost their places through\nthe return 4'-t!!f'n trom t1w -war Amt 't hi- j\nlack of employment, Miss .Mary Anderson.!\ndirector of the women's bureau of tho'\nLnited States depai tment of labor, re\nports. \"Statements to the bureau from hun\ndreds of indiisny heads who employed\nonly women dming the war show they\nhave letained their female help, while\nothers state they have replaced their wo\nmen with male woikeis,\" Miss Ander\nson said.\n''Because of the volume of unemploy\nment throughout t lie country today no\naccurate tiguies as. to the number of wo\nmen employed in industries at present\nas compared with the war peiiod are\nobtainable.\n\"I believe that when figures of the 19\"2\ncensus are available, they will show more\nthan l'.?.oP0,000 women in gainful occupa\ntion. The census, however, will not set\nforth the present situation because unem\nployment has increased l.y leaps and\nbo'.mds since it was taken.\n\"Women won the admiration of cn\nph vers during the wai period by their\nability to fill in on men's jobs. Tako for\ninstance lathe operators. Thousands of\nwomen became very efficient and still\nretain their places loside men operators.\nThe war gave American women a new op\nportunity in industry and they grasped\nit.\"\nThere are two factors needed to insure\nwomen their place in industty. Miss An\nderson said. Protective legislation for the\neight hour day is badly needed, she de\nclared, and added that the women must\n\"oriranize within the next few ears.\"\nWith the return of prosperity, indus\ntries will clamor for women workers, in\nthe opinion of Miss Mary E. McDowell\nof the University of Chicago settlenic it\nhouse, who is chairman of the women in\nindustry committee of the National\nLeague of Women Voters.\nrrescrroi\na.\nBring Your\nions\nHere\nIf you want them filled with the pnret\n&ni freshest drugs, and with th rr.-it-tt\ncare and accuracy filled precisely\nas your physician orders them filled, to\noroduce the exact effects he desires.\nWe are proud of the record we have\nmade In our prescription department.\nnd yet we fill prescriptlone at .very\nreasonable prices, and fill them jnlckly\ntoo.\nC. F. Thomas, Ph. G.\nInterest Begins Today at 7\nin our Partial Taymr-nt Department on all payments received.\n7\nThe following table shows what 10.00 a month will do:\n1st Payment S10.00 Interest 9 months at 7 per cent, .53\n2nd Payment SIO.OO interest 8 months at 7 per cent, .47\n3rd Payment SIO.OO\n4th Payment $10.00 Il5lerest 7 months at 7 per cent. .41\n5th Payment S10 00 Interest C months at 7 per cent, .35\notli Payment SIO.OO Interest 5 months at 7 per cent, .20\n7th Payment SIO.OO Interest 4 months at 7 per cent, .23\n8th Payment SIO.OO Interest 3 months at 7 per cent. .18\n0th Payment $10.00 Interest 2 months at 7 per cent, .12\n10th Payment SIO.OO Interest 1 month at 7 per cent, .00\nSIOO.OO S2.64\n7\nUpon receipt of the